Stop crashing your Server-Side Rendered apps and mixing DOM mutations. Here is how to build an enterprise-grade theme manager in modern Angular.
Implementing a dark mode toggle sounds like a trivial task. You fetch a string from local storage, push a class to the body tag, and call it a day.
However, when you move from a pet project to an enterprise-grade Angular application, things break instantly. If you are using Server-Side Rendering (SSR) or Hydration, checking window or localStorage directly will cause your application to crash during server execution before it even boots. Furthermore, ignoring real-time operating system theme toggles or mutating the DOM directly without Angular’s abstraction layers creates unmaintainable runtime architectural issues.
In this article, we will build a production-ready, bulletproof ColorSchemeService leveraging Angular Signals, Renderer2, and Platform Tokens to manage LIGHT, DARK, and SYSTEM theme mechanics seamlessly.
The Architectural Pillars
To build a reliable theme engine, we must enforce four hard boundaries:

• Reactive State Management: The current theme status must be globally accessible and reactive. We will use Angular Signals for crystal-clear, boilerplate-free state propagation.

• SSR Boundary Protection: We must safeguard any access to browser-native APIs (window, document, localStorage). If the code executes on the server, it must fail safely without throwing reference errors.

• Safe DOM Manipulation: Direct access to document.body.classList bypasses Angular's rendering pipeline. We must decouple DOM interactions using Renderer2.

• Real-time OS Synchronization: If a user selects the SYSTEM option, the application must listen to OS-level environment changes and switch colors dynamically without requiring a page reload.
The Production-Ready Implementation
Here is the complete enterprise-grade implementation. Notice how we decouple the environment checks and group responsibilities inside private abstraction layers:
import { inject, Injectable, PLATFORM_ID, RendererFactory2, signal } from "@angular/core";
import { DOCUMENT, isPlatformBrowser } from "@angular/common";
import { LocaleStorage } from "./local-storage.service"; // Reference to your custom storage abstraction
import { Theme } from "../types/design.type";@Injectable({ providedIn: "root" })
export class ColorSchemeService {
private readonly _renderer = inject(RendererFactory2).createRenderer(null, null);
private readonly _document = inject(DOCUMENT);
private readonly _platformId = inject(PLATFORM_ID);
private readonly _localStorage = inject(LocaleStorage);
private readonly _isBrowser = isPlatformBrowser(this._platformId);
readonly currentTheme = signal<Theme>(this._getSavedTheme() || "SYSTEM");
initDesign(): void {
if (!this._isBrowser) return;
window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)')
.addEventListener('change', (): void => {
if (this.currentTheme() === "SYSTEM") {
this._applySystemTheme();
}
});
const savedTheme = this._getSavedTheme();
if (savedTheme) {
this._applyTheme(savedTheme);
} else {
this._applySystemTheme();
}
}
setLightTheme(): void {
this._updateTheme("LIGHT");
}
setDarkTheme(): void {
this._updateTheme("DARK");
}
setSystemTheme(): void {
this._updateTheme("SYSTEM");
}
isSystemDark(): boolean {
return this._isBrowser && window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches;
}
private _updateTheme(theme: Theme): void {
this.currentTheme.set(theme);
if (theme === "SYSTEM") {
this._removeSavedTheme();
this._applySystemTheme();
} else {
this._saveTheme(theme);
this._applyTheme(theme);
}
}
private _applyTheme(theme: Exclude<Theme, "SYSTEM">): void {
if (theme === "DARK") {
this._renderer.addClass(this._document.body, 'dark');
} else {
this._renderer.removeClass(this._document.body, 'dark');
}
}
private _applySystemTheme(): void {
this._applyTheme(this.isSystemDark() ? "DARK" : "LIGHT");
}
private _getSavedTheme(): Theme | null {
return this._isBrowser ? (this._localStorage.getItem('theme') as Theme) : null;
}
private _saveTheme(theme: Theme): void {
if (this._isBrowser) {
this._localStorage.setItem('theme', theme);
}
}
private _removeSavedTheme(): void {
if (this._isBrowser) {
this._localStorage.removeItem('theme');
}
}
}
Deconstructing the Architecture
1. Preventing SSR Hydration Crashes
private readonly _isBrowser = isPlatformBrowser(this._platformId);By injecting the PLATFORM_ID token, we explicitly determine the execution context. If our application is running on the server during pre-rendering, _isBrowser evaluates to false. Every browser-specific block, including storage queries and media queries, is immediately short-circuited. No crashes, no hydration mismatches.
2. Declarative State via Signals
Instead of exposing standard mutable variables or dealing with complex RxJS BehaviorSubjects that require manual unsubscription handling, we introduce a read-only Signal exposed to the outside world. Components can now bind to currentTheme() natively in templates with zero change detection overhead.
3. Real-Time System Syncing
When a user sets their preference to SYSTEM, they expect the app to mimic their OS configuration. Using window.matchMedia, we attach a native event listener:
window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)')
.addEventListener('change', (): void => {
if (this.currentTheme() === "SYSTEM") {
this._applySystemTheme();
}
});If the user transitions their macOS or Windows environment from light to dark mode at sunset, our Angular application instantly mutates the DOM classes in the background without requiring a hard refresh.
4. Safe UI Mutations via Renderer2
Directly manipulating elements makes code brittle and tightly coupled to browser platforms. By leveraging RendererFactory2 to generate a structured renderer instance, we create a platform-agnostic abstraction layer for mutating global layout classes safely:
this._renderer.addClass(this._document.body, 'dark');Conclusion
Dark mode is no longer an afterthought — it’s a core UX requirement. However, cutting corners with direct DOM queries and un-guarded storage logic will degrade your software architecture. Wrapping platform checks, native media queries, and reactive state into a centralized, SSR-safe service ensures your modern Angular application remains clean, robust, and scalable.
